 <sec class="sec">
  <div class="title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Patterns in effort, catch and CPUE from creel surveys</div>
  <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Line fishing was the most commonly employed gear type at all the sites except for one (94% of the sites; 
   <a ref-type="table" rid="table-3" href="#table-3">Table 3</a>), with net fishing (primarily cast nets) being most commonly used at Hā‘ena, Kaua‘i (surveyed 2009–2010) (6% of the sites; 
   <a ref-type="table" rid="table-3" href="#table-3">Table 3</a>). In all cases where the estimate of fishing effort was quantified in hours, line fishing had the highest estimate of effort (
   <a ref-type="table" rid="table-3" href="#table-3">Table 3</a>). On average, line fishing was almost 80% of the total shore fishing effort with only 7% and 14% from net and spear fishing, respectively. However, the most efficient gear types (i.e., highest CPUE) were spear (
